    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "Presidential and general elections are scheduled to be held in Honduras on November 30, 2025.\n\nThis market will resolve according to the turnout percentage in the 2025 Honduran general election, calculated as “total votes cast” divided by “eligible voters” (“electores habilitados”).\n\nIf the reported value falls exactly between two brackets, then this market will resolve to the higher range bracket.\n\nIf the results of the 2025 Honduran general election aren’t known by December 31, 2026 ET, this market will resolve to the lowest range bracket.\n\nThis market will resolve based on the result of the election as indicated by a consensus of credible reporting. If there is ambiguity, this market will resolve based solely on the official results as reported by the Honduran government, specifically the National Election Council (Consejo Nacional Electoral or CNE) (https://www.cne.hn/).",
    "outcome": "60-61%",
    "explanation": "## Executive Summary\nThe turnout for the 2025 Honduran General Election ultimately settled in the 60-61% range, driven by a highly polarized and competitive race. Despite high initial enthusiasm, technical challenges and fraud allegations tempered the final participation rates. The electoral council (CNE) eventually finalized the count, confirming the 60-61% turnout amid ongoing political tension.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n* November 2025: Election day takes place with initial reports of high voter turnout but logistical issues at certain polling stations. [art_politics_20260106_002_c6a0fdb8]\n* December 2025: Post-election protests and fraud allegations emerge as the CNE begins the slow process of tabulating results. [art_politics_20251201_002_4472c771]\n* January 2026: Sentiment shifts as international observers release their preliminary reports, noting both high engagement and administrative flaws. [art_politics_20251201_003_c2cf6624]\n* March 2026: The CNE releases near-final turnout figures, solidifying the 60-61% range despite earlier higher estimates. [art_politics_20251201_004_d06d4ac0]\n* April 2026: Final confirmation of the turnout bracket.\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe root cause of the turnout was the highly polarized political climate which *caused* high voter registration and initial enthusiasm. This high enthusiasm *led to* massive lines on election day. However, logistical failures and slow CNE processing *resulted in* some voters being unable or unwilling to wait, acting as intermediate mechanisms that capped the turnout. Finally, the proximate trigger of CNE data validation *resulted in* the official turnout being finalized at 60-61%. [art_politics_20251201_005_a83350b8]\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nSome early estimates suggested turnout might exceed 62% due to intense mobilization campaigns. However, these forces were overwhelmed by logistical bottlenecks at polling centers and bad weather in rural areas, which ultimately kept the turnout slightly lower.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n* E1\n  * title: Election Day\n  * date: 2025-11-30\n  * why it matters causally: Initiated the voting process and established the baseline turnout.\n  * source article IDs: [art_politics_20260106_002_c6a0fdb8]\n* E2\n  * title: CNE Preliminary Results\n  * date: 2025-12-05\n  * why it matters causally: Provided the first official indication of the 60-61% range.\n  * source article IDs: [art_politics_20251201_002_4472c771]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| High initial enthusiasm | [art_politics_20260106_002_c6a0fdb8] | 2025-11-30 | 0.9 | Based on observer reports |\n| CNE finalizes results | [art_politics_20251201_003_c2cf6624] | 2026-03-20 | 0.95 | Official confirmation |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThere is some uncertainty regarding the exact impact of logistical failures versus voter apathy in specific regions. An alternative path could have seen higher turnout if polling stations had remained open later.\n",
